			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">(They will press criminal charges against her) 
<br />

<br />
I find it incredulous that someone who gets their legal understandings from the tabloid headlines behind the checkout stand, is giving advice to an individual that is staring down the barrel of a criminal conviction.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Corporations don't magically indict people.  The corporation would have to make their case to the DA/police and *then* the Police/DA decide.  Companies don't have magical powers to charge and convict people on Embezzlement crimes.  Unless there is overwhelming evidence such as a videotape of an employee stuffing property into their trunk or the dollar amount of the crime is *very* high the Police will not investigate the crime.  They will tell the company to seek retribution in the civil court.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Are those WORTH a 2 week paycheque because you pissed off the company with your namby pamby threats that you’re going to sue them for your final paycheque? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
There is no namby-pampy threats.  You go to the Labor board.  The labor board goes to the company and says to pay this person or they will be fined massive ammounts of money and/or shut down.  If they do not pay they are fined, assets seized, business license revoked. There is no sueing, there is no threats.  If the company wants to try and fight this in court (Against the labor board not you) they will lose more money paying lawyers than it would take to pay off the employee. That's how the law is in the US when it comes to labor, very much slanted towards the worker.  Go ahead and thank Unions if you want.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
