				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Zophia wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">There is no namby-pampy threats.  You go to the Labor board.  The labor board goes to the company and says to pay this person or they will be fined massive ammounts of money and/or shut down.  If they do not pay they are fined, assets seized, business license revoked. There is no sueing, there is no threats.  If the company wants to try and fight this in court (Against the labor board not you) they will lose more money paying lawyers than it would take to pay off the employee. That's how the law is in the US when it comes to labor, very much slanted towards the worker.  Go ahead and thank Unions if you want.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Unless of course you work on base salary/commission. The labor board won't have anything to do with commission or base salary. Only if there is a "time-clock", where you can prove you went to work. At least in Florida anyway. This happen to my dad, when he left his old company. So he "lost" half year of commission and a month salary.
<br />

<br />
There is a old saying, "The one with the most money wins". If you get the labor board to fight for you. Labor board got more money. I've spent enough time with the "good old boys" of Florida. So yes, I'm jaded.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
