I think this article relates. . .
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3079359/" target="_blank">http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3079359/</a>
<br />

<br />
They finally produced the documentation and accounting they dug up while she was on vacation.  It's pretty serious.
<br />

<br />
She definately has a problem, looks like compulsive spending.
<br />

<br />
Technically, she didn't feel she was <span style="font-style: italic">stealing</span>, she coded everything she did as "advances" to herself.  Including the company credit card charges that were for personal use and she would later pay them back.
<br />

<br />
However, in the 8 months, she had "advanced" herself <span style="font-weight: bold">$13,000 </span>worth of cash and credit card charges.   <img src="images/smiles/eusa_eh.gif" alt="Eh?" border="0" />    She would have to forfeit every paycheck for the <span style="text-decoration: underline">next 5 months</span> to pay it back.  She would take a $1,300 draw, and pay back $500, then next month draw $1,300 and pay back $500, etc.  Right before the vacation, she took another $1,800 draw (which her boss actually ok'd, but had no idea how much she already had advanced).  Plus all the personal credit card charges on the company account.
<br />

<br />
I wish something had been done sooner.  I wish I could have stopped it before it happened.  But she definately was out of control.  I certainly don't blame the company for firing her now.
<br />

<br />
The company has given her 30 days to pay back the rest of the money.  It's going to be fun finding a way to do that. . .
